Superstorm Sandy may cost insurers
$20 billion to $25 billion after striking the U.S. Northeast
last month, according to an estimate provided to clients by Risk
Management Solutions Inc.  The figure compares with a projection of as much a $20
billion from Eqecat Inc., another modeling firm. The RMS range
was stated today on a conference call by Kevin Oâ€™Donnell, global
chief underwriting officer at  RenaissanceRe Holdings Ltd. (RNR)   Carolyn Camp, a spokeswoman for RMS, confirmed the figures.  To contact the reporter on this story:
